Chapter 12: Multivariate Regression

Todays class will be based on Chapter 12: Multiple Regression. Have you read it? We will be using data on college characteristics from the IPEDS Database and the Scorecard created by the Department of Education, gathered via the Opportunity Insights project. The codebook with explanations for each variable is here. We will be trying to figure out what characteristics of a college are associated with the 2011 median income of students, earnings, 10 years after they graduate. The other data faculty, the average faculty salary; sat, the average SAT score; tier, the type of college; public, the private/public status; and price, tuition is reported as of 2001.

Scene 2

Prompt: Whats the correlation between the average faculty salary in 2001 and the median income of students 10 years after entering? Whats the correlation between the average SAT scores in 2001 and the median income of students 10 years after entering? Find these by doing two separate correlations first, and then making a correlation matrix (instructions in the book).

# finding correlations using separate correlations

x %>% 
  summarize(correlation = cor(faculty, earnings))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   correlation
##         <dbl>
## 1       0.674
x %>% 
  summarize(correlation = cor(sat, earnings))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   correlation
##         <dbl>
## 1       0.604
# finding correlations using a correlation matrix

x %>% 
  select(faculty, sat, earnings) %>% 
  cor()
##            faculty       sat  earnings
## faculty  1.0000000 0.6359926 0.6737729
## sat      0.6359926 1.0000000 0.6041897
## earnings 0.6737729 0.6041897 1.0000000

Scene 3

Prompt: Visualize the relationships between the outcome variable (earnings) and the two key numerical explanatory variables (faculty and sat), one at a time. Create a ggplot for each showing the line of best fit.

x %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = faculty, y = earnings)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Average Faculty Salary", y = "Median Earnings of Students") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

x %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = sat, y = earnings)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Average SAT scores in 2001", y = "Median Earnings of Students") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

Scene 6

Prompt: Imagine that you are the university president. Theres a global pandemic that is causing serious financial damage to the school endowment, and in response, you want to cut the financial aid budget. However, because many academically talented students will go to whichever school gives them the best financial aid package, slashing the financial aid budget will cause the average SAT score to decrease from 1400 to 1300. Apply the Rubin Causal Model to frame the causal effect of this policy change on the median earnings of students 10 years from now. Write down the units, the treatments, and the outcomes. Define the causal effect of the policy change on median earnings. What is the fundamental problem of causal inference? What must you assume for this causal model to make a causal claim?

Scene 7

Prompt: Recall the model we made in Scene 4. Use that model to make a prediction. Consider a school with average faculty salary of $50,000 and average SAT of 1400. What would the the median students earnings be 10 years from now? Although there are fancier ways of doing this in R check out the predict() function you should use the simple approach of using the regression estimates and then plugging in the appropriate values. Then, what would happen if a change in financial aid were to drop the average SAT score to 1300? What would you forecast earnings to be in that case? Putting the two together: What is the causal effect of the drop in SAT? Do you believe that? That is, if you were the university president, would you believe that forecast?
